data.content:
Here are the better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    foreach (var u in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive, $"User {u.Name} is not active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count());

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x)` | Shows actual value on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x)` | Shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer failure message |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The main benefit is better failure messages — `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count())` tells you "Expected: 3, Actual: 5" instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
